🧠 RFH vs FL – Computational Pathology Models

This repository contains the modelling pipeline used in the study “Classification of Reactive Follicular Hyperplasia (RFH) and Follicular Lymphoma (FL)”, integrating histopathological images, 
cell-level spatial organisation, morphometric features, and clinicopathological data.

The project combines:
Deep learning (CNNs and Vision Transformers)
Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)
Multimodal learning
Classical machine learning with statistical interpretability


📘 Model Categories
1. Multimodal Deep Learning

These scripts combine histopathological image features with clinical variables to improve diagnostic performance.

             Script                    │     Level     │                            **Description**
multimodal_alexnet_patch_level.py	   │     Patch     │       AlexNet architecture for patch-level multimodal fusion.
multimodal_alexnet_patient_level.py	   │    Patient    │         Aggregated patient-level model using mean feature pooling.
multimodal_resnet18_patch_level.py	   │     Patch     │   ResNet18-based model integrating local image patches and tabular data.
multimodal_resnet18_patient_level.py   │    Patient    │         ResNet18 model trained on patient-level aggregated embeddings.
multimodal_vgg16_patch_level.py	       │     Patch     │       VGG16 model for multimodal feature learning at the patch level.
multimodal_vgg16_patient_level.py	   │    Patient    │         VGG16 architecture applied at patient-level granularity.


All multimodal models include:
Late fusion between CNN features and clinical embeddings
Weighted loss functions for class imbalance
ROC/PR curve generation
Support for multi-GPU training (torch.nn.DataParallel)


2. Cell-Level Vision Transformers (CellViT++)
🔎 Important note on implementation
CellViT++ are established, peer-reviewed architectures.
In this study, their original implementations were used without architectural modifications.

For this reason:
The full source code of CellViT++ is not redistributed in this repository
Only wrapper scripts and downstream analysis pipelines are provided
All hyperparameters and configurations used are fully documented below

Purpose
Nuclear segmentation
Cell-level feature extraction
Morphometric and appearance embeddings

Hyperparameters and configuration
Architecture: Vision Transformer–based (CellViT++)
Input size: 256 × 256 pixels
Magnification: 40×
Pretraining: As provided in the original CellViT++ release

Output:
Binary nuclear masks
Cell-level embeddings
Morphometric descriptors (area, eccentricity, etc.)

Mode: Inference only (no retraining)
Framework: PyTorch
Precision: Mixed precision (CUDA)

Usage in this project
Outputs from CellViT++ are used as inputs for:
XGBoost models
Cell Graph Neural Network (Cell-GNN)
Multimodal learning pipelines

3. Cell Graph Neural Network (Cell-GNN)
🔎 Important note on implementation
Cell-GNN is a previously established graph-based framework.
The original implementation was used without architectural changes.

Thus:
The full Cell-GNN source code is not duplicated here
Only preprocessing, graph construction, and analysis scripts are included
Hyperparameters are explicitly reported

Purpose
To model cell–cell spatial relationships and quantify tissue organisation patterns.

Graph construction
Nodes: Cell nuclei centroids
Edge definition: k-nearest neighbours (k = 8)
Distance metric: Euclidean distance
Graph type: Undirected
Self-loops: Disabled

GNN architecture and hyperparameters
GNN type: GraphSAGE
Number of layers: 3
Hidden dimension: 128
Node embedding dimension: 128
Aggregation: Mean
Activation: ReLU
Normalisation: Batch Normalisation
Dropout: 0.3

Training / inference configuration
Optimiser: AdamW
Learning rate: 1 × 10⁻³
Weight decay: 1 × 10⁻⁴
Batch size: 16 graphs
Epochs: 100
Early stopping: Patience = 15
Random seed: Fixed

Outputs
Mean intercellular distance per patch
Patch- and patient-level graph descriptors
Statistical features for group comparison

4. Image Segmentation (CNN-based)
              Script	                       Model                                  Description
segmentation_unet++.py             	   │    U-Net++    │         U-Net++ with attention gates for tissue segmentation

5. Classical Machine Learning
Script	                                     Model                                  Description
xgboost_classification_cpc_mpa.R	     │    U-Net++    │        XGBoost on clinicopathological and morphometric features
xgboost_classification_gradcam.R	     │    U-Net++    │                XGBoost on Grad-CAM–derived features

Features
Train / validation / test split
Feature importance plots
Confusion matrix and ROC/PR curves
CSV export to /results/

⚙️ Patch Generation and Pre-processing
Patch size: 299 × 299 pixels
Overlap: 20%
Colour normalisation: Macenko
Data augmentation:
Rotations (90°, 180°, 270°)
Gaussian blur

Dataset split
Training: 80% (73 cases, 276,823 patches)
Validation: 10% (9 cases, 32,043 patches)
Test: 10% (8 cases, 31,939 patches)
External validation: 2 cohorts (9 cases each)

Final dataset size
Training: 1,384,115 patches
Validation: 160,215 patches
Test: 159,695 patches

🧬 Reproducibility
Python: 3.12.11
PyTorch: 2.8.0 + CUDA 12.8
GPUs: 3 × NVIDIA RTX 3090 (24 GB)
OS: Ubuntu 20.04 LTS
RAM: 125 GB
Determinism ensured via fixed random seeds (torch, numpy, random)

📎 Reproducibility Statement
Although CellViT / CellViT++ and Cell-GNN implementations are not redistributed, all results can be fully reproduced by:
Using the original public implementations
Applying the exact hyperparameters reported in this README
Running the provided preprocessing, inference, and analysis scripts

